NOTES_PHILIPPIANS = {
    1: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Bondservants" (δοῦλοι, douloi, G1401) denotes slaves—those wholly owned by a master. Paul deliberately places himself and Timothy in this subordinate role to Christ Jesus. "Overseers" (ἐπισκόποις, episkopois, G1985) and "deacons" (διακόνοις, diakonois, G1249) represent the earliest attested dual structure of local church leadership. HISTORICAL: Philippi was a Roman colonia in Macedonia, where Paul founded the first European church (Acts 16:12-40). The mention of structured offices suggests a maturing congregation approximately ten years after its founding.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Grace" (χάρις, charis) and "peace" (εἰρήνη, eirēnē) combine Greco-Roman and Hebrew (shalom) greeting forms, signifying the unification of Jew and Gentile in one new humanity. Paul coordinates God the Father and the Lord Jesus Christ as co-source of divine grace and peace, placing the Lord Jesus in a position of functional equality with the Father (cf. 2 Cor 13:14).',
        5: 'GREEK: "Fellowship" (κοινωνίᾳ, koinōnia, G2842) denotes active partnership and participation, not mere association. The Philippians\' koinōnia "in the gospel" (εἰς τὸ εὐαγγέλιον) includes both spiritual solidarity and material financial support (cf. Phil 4:15-16). HISTORICAL: The Philippians were the only church that entered into a giving-and-receiving partnership with Paul from the beginning of his mission work.',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "good work" (ἔργον ἀγαθόν) begun by God himself assures the believer of divine perseverance unto completion. The "day of Christ Jesus" (ἡμέρας Χριστοῦ Ἰησοῦ) is an eschatological reference to the return and final appearing of Christ (cf. 1 Cor 1:8; 2 Cor 1:14). GREEK: "Began" (ἐναρξάμενος, enarxamenos, G1728) is a rare term used in sacrificial contexts for the inauguration of a sacred rite, suggesting God\'s work in believers has a consecrated, covenantal character.',
        10: 'GREEK: "Approve the things that are excellent" (δοκιμάζειν τὰ διαφέροντα) may also be rendered "test the things that differ"—the verb δοκιμάζω (G1381) denotes assaying metals for genuineness. "Sincere" (εἰλικρινεῖς, eilikrineis, G1506) etymologically suggests "judged by sunlight," that is, tested by the light and found pure. THEOLOGICAL: Moral discernment is here presented not as mere human wisdom but as a fruit of love abounding in knowledge—an epistemology rooted in sanctified affection.',
        13: 'HISTORICAL: The "praetorium" (πραιτωρίῳ, praitōriō, G4232) likely refers to the Praetorian Guard—the imperial bodyguard stationed in Rome—or to the governor\'s residence if Paul was imprisoned elsewhere. Either way, Paul\'s chains became an occasion for the gospel to penetrate the highest levels of Roman imperial power (cf. Phil 4:22). GREEK: The Latin loanword praitōrion entered Greek through Roman military administration.',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The supply of the Spirit of Jesus Christ" (ἐπιχορηγίας τοῦ πνεύματος Ἰησοῦ Χριστοῦ) is a remarkable title identifying the Holy Spirit as belonging to and proceeding from Jesus Christ (cf. Rom 8:9; Gal 4:6). GREEK: "Supply" (ἐπιχορηγία, epichorēgia, G2024) originally denoted the lavish funding of a chorus by a wealthy patron—implying the Spirit is given abundantly, not sparingly.',
        21: 'THEOLOGICAL: This is one of the most compressed christological statements in the Pauline corpus. "To live is Christ" (τὸ ζῆν Χριστός) identifies Christ not merely as the reason for living but as the very content and substance of life itself. Death becomes "gain" (κέρδος, kerdos, G2771) only because it brings unmediated presence with Christ (v. 23). This verse demolishes any framework that separates existence from christological orientation.',
        23: 'GREEK: "Hard pressed" (συνέχομαι, synechomai, G4912) means to be constrained or hemmed in from both sides. "Departing" (ἀναλῦσαι, analysai, G360) is a metaphor drawn from loosing a ship from its moorings or striking a military camp—a vivid image of death as departure toward Christ. "Very much more better" (πολλῷ μᾶλλον κρεῖσσον) stacks three comparative expressions, an unusual Greek intensification revealing the depth of Paul\'s longing.',
        27: 'GREEK: "Conduct yourselves worthily" (πολιτεύεσθε, politeuesthe, G4176) is a politically charged verb meaning "live as citizens." In the Roman colonia of Philippi, where citizens prized their Roman politeia, Paul redirects civic identity toward the heavenly commonwealth (cf. Phil 3:20). THEOLOGICAL: The unity of "one spirit" (ἑνὶ πνεύματι) and "one soul" (μιᾷ ψυχῇ) likely distinguishes the Holy Spirit\'s enabling from the believers\' united inner resolve. "Striving together" (συναθλοῦντες, G4866) is an athletic metaphor—competing side by side as teammates.',
        29: 'THEOLOGICAL: Suffering is here presented as a gracious gift (ἐχαρίσθη, from χαρίζομαι, G5483—cognate with χάρις, "grace") granted on behalf of Christ. Both faith and suffering are parallel gifts from God, placing persecution within the economy of divine grace rather than outside it. This reframes the Philippians\' affliction as a mark of divine favor, not divine abandonment (cf. Acts 5:41; 1 Pet 4:12-14).',
    },
    2: {
        1: 'GREEK: παράκλησις (paraklēsis, Strong\'s G3874) means "encouragement" or "exhortation," from the same root as παράκλητος (paraklētos), the title given to the Holy Spirit in John 14:16. The fourfold "if" (εἴ τις) structure is a first-class conditional in Greek, assuming the reality of each condition — Paul is not expressing doubt but appealing to what they already experience in Christ. σπλάγχνα (splanchna, G4698) refers to the inner organs regarded as the seat of deep emotion.',
        2: 'STRUCTURE: Paul employs four parallel phrases to define the unity he desires: "think the same thing," "having the same love," "united in soul," "thinking the one thing." The verb φρονέω (phroneō, G5426) — to think, to set one\'s mind — appears twice, framing the exhortation and forming a key word throughout the chapter (vv. 2, 3, 5).',
        3: 'GREEK: ἐριθεία (eritheia, G2052) originally denoted a day-laborer\'s self-seeking work for hire; by Paul\'s usage it means factious, selfish ambition. κενοδοξία (kenodoxia, G2754) is a compound of κενός ("empty") and δόξα ("glory") — literally "empty glory." ταπεινοφροσύνη (tapeinophrosunē, G5012) — "humility of mind" — was considered a vice in Greco-Roman culture but is here elevated as a Christian virtue.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse introduces the great Christ-hymn (vv. 5-11). The imperative φρονεῖτε (phroneite) calls the Philippians to adopt the very mindset (φρόνησις) of Christ Jesus himself, establishing the incarnation not merely as theology but as ethical pattern for the community.',
        6: 'GREEK: μορφή (morphē, G3444) signifies the essential form or nature — not mere outward appearance (σχῆμα). Christ existing (ὑπάρχων, a present participle indicating continuous prior existence) in the form of God means he possessed the very nature of deity. ἁρπαγμός (harpagmos, G725) is a rare term (near hapax in NT) debated as either "something seized" or "something to be exploited." The sense is that Christ did not regard his divine equality as something to be clutched or used for self-advantage. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The assertion of equality (ἴσα) with God places the pre-incarnate Christ at the supreme position of the divine council, co-equal with the Father before all created spiritual beings.',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: ἐκένωσεν (ekenōsen, from κενόω, G2758) — "he emptied himself" — is the foundation of kenosis theology. This does not imply a loss of divine nature but a voluntary relinquishment of divine prerogatives. The taking of δούλου μορφήν ("the form of a bondservant") is a deliberate descent from the highest station to the lowest. TYPOLOGY: The "form of a bondservant" echoes the Suffering Servant of Isaiah 52:13-53:12 (LXX παῖς/δοῦλος). Christ fulfills the Isaianic Servant who takes on affliction for the sake of others.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: The descent reaches its nadir: self-humbling, obedience unto death, and specifically σταυροῦ (stauros) — death of a cross, the most shameful Roman execution reserved for slaves and insurrectionists. The word δέ introduces "death of a cross" as a shocking intensification. HISTORICAL: Crucifixion was so despised that Cicero called it "the most cruel and disgusting penalty" (In Verrem 2.5.165). For a Roman colony like Philippi, this language carried maximum rhetorical force.',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: διό ("therefore") marks the turning point — the exaltation answers the humiliation. ὑπερύψωσεν (hyperypsoō, G5251) appears only here in the NT, meaning "super-exalted" or "exalted to the highest degree." God grants (ἐχαρίσατο, from χαρίζομαι — a gracious bestowal) the name above every name. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The granting of the supreme name (τὸ ὄνομα τὸ ὑπὲρ πᾶν ὄνομα) implies enthronement over all heavenly powers, principalities, and every member of the divine council — a cosmic investiture of authority (cf. Eph 1:20-21).',
        10: 'TYPOLOGY: This is a direct echo of Isaiah 45:23 (LXX), where YHWH declares that every knee shall bow to him alone. Paul applies this text — a monotheistic declaration of YHWH\'s sole sovereignty — directly to Jesus. The three-tiered cosmos (ἐπουρανίων, ἐπιγείων, καταχθονίων — heavenly, earthly, and under-the-earth beings) encompasses all spiritual and physical reality, including angelic beings, the living, and the dead.',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: The confession κύριος Ἰησοῦς Χριστός ("Jesus Christ is Lord") is likely the earliest Christian creedal formula. That this universal confession redounds εἰς δόξαν θεοῦ πατρός ("to the glory of God the Father") shows that Christ\'s lordship does not compete with but rather fulfills the Father\'s purpose. GREEK: ἐξομολογήσηται (exomologēsetai, G1843) means "to openly and gladly confess" — not a forced admission but an acknowledgment of reality.',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse provides the theological ground for verse 12. The imperative to "work out" salvation is not self-reliance; it is empowered by God\'s sovereign working (ἐνεργῶν, energōn, G1754 — from which English "energy" derives). God is the one producing both τὸ θέλειν ("the willing") and τὸ ἐνεργεῖν ("the working"), revealing that divine sovereignty and human responsibility operate in concert, not opposition. εὐδοκίας (eudokias, G2107) — "good pleasure" — emphasizes God\'s gracious, sovereign delight as the motive.',
        15: 'TYPOLOGY: The phrase γενεᾶς σκολιᾶς καὶ διεστραμμένης ("a crooked and perverted generation") directly echoes Deuteronomy 32:5 (LXX), from the Song of Moses, where Israel is rebuked for unfaithfulness. Paul applies this to the pagan world surrounding the Philippians, casting the church as the true faithful children of God. φωστῆρες (phōstēres, G5458) means "luminaries" or "stars" — used in the LXX of Genesis 1:14-16 for the heavenly lights, elevating believers to a cosmic witness role.',
        17: 'GREEK: σπένδομαι (spendomai, G4689) — "I am being poured out as a drink offering" — is a sacrificial term used in the LXX for the wine libation poured over a burnt offering (Num 15:5-7). Paul views his potential martyrdom as a secondary offering poured upon the primary sacrifice — which is the Philippians\' own faith (θυσίᾳ καὶ λειτουργίᾳ τῆς πίστεως ὑμῶν). λειτουργία (leitourgia, G3009) is a priestly/liturgical term, framing their faith as a sacred offering to God.',
        25: 'GREEK: Paul stacks five titles for Epaphroditus: ἀδελφόν (brother), συνεργόν (fellow-worker), συστρατιώτην (fellow-soldier) — relating to Paul; then ἀπόστολον (apostle/messenger) and λειτουργόν (minister/liturgist) — relating to the Philippians. ἀπόστολος here carries its broader sense of "sent one" or "emissary" rather than the technical apostolic office. HISTORICAL: Epaphroditus was the Philippians\' delegate who brought their financial gift to Paul in prison (Phil 4:18) and nearly died serving him.',
        30: 'GREEK: παραβολευσάμενος (paraboleusamenos) — "having risked" — is an exceptionally rare word, a gambling term meaning "having staked" or "having hazarded" his life. Some manuscripts read παραβουλευσάμενος. The term evokes the reckless courage of one who throws the dice with his own existence. THEOLOGICAL: Epaphroditus\'s near-death service to Paul is presented as filling up (ἀναπληρώσῃ) what the Philippian congregation could not do in person — an act of representative, vicarious ministry that mirrors in a lesser way the self-giving of Christ in the hymn above (vv. 6-8).',
    },
    3: {
        2: 'GREEK: "Kynас" (κύνας, dogs) was a term of contempt applied to those outside the covenant. "Katatomēn" (κατατομήν, mutilation) is a sharp wordplay on "peritomē" (circumcision) in v.3 — Paul deliberately uses the prefix κατα- (down/against) to mock those demanding circumcision of Gentile believers, reducing their rite to mere cutting of flesh. THEOLOGICAL: The threefold "blépete" (beware/look out) creates an urgent rhetorical triplet warning against Judaizing opponents.',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: Paul radically redefines circumcision: the true "peritomē" (περιτομή) is not physical but spiritual — those who worship by the Spirit of God. This echoes Deut 30:6 and Jer 4:4 where the prophets spoke of circumcision of the heart. DIVINE_COUNCIL: "Pneumati theou latreuontes" — worship rendered by God\'s Spirit marks the true covenant community, the heavenly assembly on earth.',
        8: 'GREEK: "Skybala" (σκύβαλα, Strong\'s G4657) is a rare and viscerally strong term meaning refuse, dung, or filth — used only here in the NT (hapax legomenon). Paul employs this shocking word to express the utter worthlessness of his former credentials compared to knowing Christ. "Hyperechon" (ὑπερέχον) denotes surpassing excellence or supremacy — the knowledge of Christ surpasses all things in worth.',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Dikaiosynēn tēn ek theou" — the righteousness from God, contrasted with self-achieved righteousness from the law, is the heart of Pauline soteriology. "Dia pisteōs Christou" may be rendered "through faith in Christ" (objective genitive) or "through the faithfulness of Christ" (subjective genitive) — both readings have ancient support. This parallels Rom 3:21-22 and Gal 2:16.',
        11: 'GREEK: "Exanastasin" (ἐξανάστασιν, Strong\'s G1815) is a NT hapax legomenon — the double-prefixed form (ek + ana + stasis) intensifies the concept beyond ordinary "anastasis," pointing to the out-resurrection from among the dead, the final eschatological resurrection of the righteous. TYPOLOGY: This ultimate resurrection hope is grounded in Christ\'s own resurrection as firstfruits (1 Cor 15:20-23).',
        14: 'GREEK: "Brabeion" (βραβεῖον, Strong\'s G1017) is the prize awarded to victors in Greek athletic games — used also in 1 Cor 9:24. "Anō klēseōs" (upward calling) denotes the heavenward summons of God. HISTORICAL: The athletic metaphor would resonate powerfully in a Roman colony like Philippi, where Greek games and Roman civic competitions were well known.',
        17: 'GREEK: "Symmimētai" (συμμιμηταί, Strong\'s G4831) is a NT hapax — a compound meaning "fellow-imitators together," not merely individual imitators but a communal imitation of Paul\'s pattern. "Typon" (τύπον) means pattern, model, or stamp — from which English "type" derives. TYPOLOGY: Paul presents himself as a living pattern of one whose life is being conformed to Christ\'s death and resurrection (vv.10-11).',
        20: 'GREEK: "Politeuma" (πολίτευμα, Strong\'s G4175) means citizenship or commonwealth — a politically charged term for residents of Philippi, a Roman colony whose citizens prized their Roman citizenship. HISTORICAL: Philippians held Roman citizenship and lived as a colony of Rome in Macedonia; Paul subverts this identity by declaring believers\' true "politeuma" is in the heavens. THEOLOGICAL: The awaited "Sōtēra" (Savior) and "Kyrion" (Lord) are titles the Roman emperor claimed — Paul assigns them exclusively to Jesus Christ.',
        21: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Metaschēmatisei" (μετασχηματίσει) means to transform or transfigure the outward form — the body of humiliation will be made "symmorphon" (conformed, sharing the same form) with Christ\'s glorified body. This is the culmination of the conformity to Christ begun in suffering (v.10). TYPOLOGY: This transformation fulfills the pattern of Adam\'s fallen body being restored and surpassed in the last Adam (1 Cor 15:42-49; Rom 8:29). The subjection of all things echoes Ps 8:6 and Ps 110:1, affirming Christ\'s universal sovereignty.',
    },
    4: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Crown" (στέφανος, stephanos, Strong\'s G4735) refers to the victor\'s wreath, not a royal diadem (diadēma). Paul views the Philippian believers as his eschatological reward, the evidence of his apostolic labor (cf. 1 Thess 2:19). "Longed-for" (ἐπιπόθητοι, epipothētoi) is rare in Greek literature and expresses deep, yearning affection. STRUCTURE: This verse serves as a hinge between the warnings of chapter 3 and the practical exhortations of chapter 4.',
        3: 'GREEK: "True yokefellow" (γνήσιε σύζυγε, gnēsie syzuge) is debated — σύζυγος could be a proper name "Syzygus" or a description of a genuine companion. "Labored together" (συνήθλησαν, synēthlēsan, Strong\'s G4866) is an athletic term meaning "contended alongside," evoking the image of the arena. THEOLOGICAL: "Book of life" (βίβλος ζωῆς) draws on OT imagery of God\'s heavenly register (Ex 32:32; Ps 69:28; Dan 12:1), carried forward into Revelation (Rev 3:5; 20:12).',
        5: 'GREEK: "Gentleness" (ἐπιεικές, epieikes, Strong\'s G1933) denotes a yielding, magnanimous reasonableness that does not insist on strict legal rights — difficult to render with a single English word. THEOLOGICAL: "The Lord is near" (ὁ κύριος ἐγγύς) carries a dual sense: the Lord\'s spatial nearness in presence and his temporal nearness in return (parousia). This echoes the Aramaic prayer "Maranatha" (1 Cor 16:22) and grounds the call to gentleness in eschatological expectation.',
        7: 'GREEK: "Surpasses" (ὑπερέχουσα, hyperechousa, Strong\'s G5242) means "rising above, excelling beyond." "Guard" (φρουρήσει, phrourēsei, Strong\'s G5432) is a military term meaning to garrison or stand sentinel — God\'s peace acts as a divine sentinel over the believer\'s inner life. THEOLOGICAL: The peace here is not subjective tranquility but the objective shalom of God himself — his own cosmic peace — standing watch over hearts and minds. The locus of this guarding is "in Christ Jesus," the covenantal sphere of divine protection.',
        8: 'GREEK: This verse employs a rhetorical device (anaphora) with the sixfold repetition of ὅσα (hosa, "whatever things"). Several terms here overlap with Greco-Roman virtue lists: σεμνά (semna, "honorable/dignified"), ἀρετή (aretē, "virtue," Strong\'s G703) — notably the only use of aretē by Paul, a term central to Greek philosophical ethics. HISTORICAL: Paul engages Hellenistic moral vocabulary familiar to the Philippian audience, demonstrating that genuine virtue, wherever found, is subsumed under and measured by the gospel.',
        12: 'GREEK: "I have been initiated" (μεμύημαι, memyēmai, Strong\'s G3453) is a perfect passive from myeō, a technical term from the Greek mystery religions meaning to be initiated into secret rites. Paul co-opts this language: his "mystery initiation" is learning contentment through Christ in all circumstances. HISTORICAL: This language would have resonated powerfully in the Greco-Roman world of Philippi, a Roman colony where mystery cults were prevalent.',
        13: 'GREEK: "I am able to do all things" (πάντα ἰσχύω, panta ischyō) — ἰσχύω (Strong\'s G2480) denotes having strength or power. "The one who strengthens me" (τῷ ἐνδυναμοῦντί με, tō endynamounti me) uses ἐνδυναμόω (Strong\'s G1743), "to empower, pour strength into." THEOLOGICAL: The "all things" must be read in context — not unlimited power for any desire, but the ability to endure all circumstances of abundance and want (vv. 11-12). The source of strength is Christ, not the self — a direct counter to Stoic self-sufficiency.',
        18: 'TYPOLOGY: "A fragrance of sweet aroma" (ὀσμὴν εὐωδίας, osmēn euōdias) directly echoes LXX sacrificial language (Gen 8:21; Ex 29:18; Lev 1:9). Paul frames the Philippians\' financial gift as a priestly offering ascending to God. "Acceptable" (δεκτήν) and "well-pleasing" (εὐάρεστον) are cultic terms applied to sacrifices God receives with favor. THEOLOGICAL: This transforms ordinary material generosity into liturgical worship, collapsing the sacred-secular divide.',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: This is a promissory declaration, not a wish — the future indicative πληρώσει ("shall fill") expresses divine certainty. God\'s supply is measured "according to" (κατά) his riches, not "out of" — the standard of giving matches the inexhaustible measure of divine glory. The phrase "in glory in Christ Jesus" locates both the riches and the fulfillment within the glorified reign of the Messiah.',
        20: 'STRUCTURE: "Unto the ages of the ages" (εἰς τοὺς αἰῶνας τῶν αἰώνων) is the strongest Greek expression for unending eternity, a Hebraism of superlative intensification (cf. Rev 1:6; Gal 1:5). THEOLOGICAL: The doxology ascribes glory to "our God and Father" — the intimate covenant language of divine fatherhood grounding all of Paul\'s theology of provision and care in this passage.',
        22: 'HISTORICAL: "Those of the household of Caesar" (οἱ ἐκ τῆς Καίσαρος οἰκίας) refers not to the imperial family but to the extensive network of slaves, freedmen, and officials in Caesar\'s administrative household — the familia Caesaris. Paul writes from imprisonment (Phil 1:13), and the gospel has penetrated even into the heart of Roman imperial power. This is a stunning testament to the advance of the gospel into the structures of the empire itself.',
    },
}